==English==

===Etymology===
# Originally French designation in 1818 of the self-propelled, two-wheeled laufmaschine or draisine, translated from German "Schnellfuss". Grimms' dictionary quotes "einen Schnellfuss machen" i.e. to make one's getaway. Official term in the UK in 1819, but soon nick-named a hobby-horse or a dandy-horse. Half a century later with cranks "le vélocipède bicycle" was nick-named a [[boneshaker]] due to its rigid construction.
# Alternative term used to describe human-powered vehicles in general from 1818 on up to recent times. ''(contemporary usage)''

